\section{Detecting tutorial changes across resumes}

Resuming a run against a different tutorial file would be confusing at
best and misleading at worst.  We therefore compare the saved source
digest against the current tutorial digest before resuming an unfinished
run.

<<functions>>=
def ensure_run_matches_tutorial(tutorial: Tutorial, run: TutorialRun) -> None:
    """Reject resuming a run if the tutorial file changed."""

    if run.tutorial_source_digest is None or tutorial.source_digest is None:
        return
    if run.tutorial_source_digest != tutorial.source_digest:
        raise RuntimeError(
            f"Tutorial {tutorial.id!r} changed since this run began. "
            "Use --restart to begin a fresh run."
        )
@


\section{Writing a sample tutorial file for tests}

Many runner tests need the same small Markdown tutorial file.  A helper
keeps that fixture stable and makes the catalog-based tests easier to
read.

<<functions>>=
def write_demo_tutorial(root_dir: str | Path) -> Path:
    """Write the sample tutorial file used by runner tests."""

    tutorial_path = Path(root_dir) / "shell-basics.md"
    tutorial_path.write_text(
        "---\n"
        "id: shell-basics\n"
        "title: Shell Basics\n"
        "summary: Inspect the workspace, create and edit a file, and review what you did.\n"
        "---\n\n"
        "# Inspect the workspace\n\n"
        "```tutorial-step\n"
        "required_patterns:\n"
        "  - pwd\n"
        "  - ls\n"
        "hint: The shell starts in the tutorial workspace.\n"
        "```\n\n"
        "Run `pwd` and `ls`.\n\n"
        "This shows where the tutorial stores its work for this run.\n\n"
        "# Create a note\n\n"
        "```tutorial-step\n"
        "check_command: test -f notes.txt\n"
        "hint: Any command sequence is fine if `notes.txt` exists afterwards.\n"
        "```\n\n"
        "Create an empty `notes.txt`.\n\n"
        "One way is:\n\n"
        "`touch notes.txt`\n\n"
        "# Edit the note\n\n"
        "```tutorial-step\n"
        "edit_file: notes.txt\n"
        "required_patterns:\n"
        "  - tutorial\n"
        "check_command: grep -q tutorial notes.txt\n"
        "hint: Save the file after adding the word `tutorial`.\n"
        "```\n\n"
        "Open `notes.txt` in your editor and add the word `tutorial`.\n\n"
        "Save the file and quit the editor so the tutorial can continue.\n\n"
        "# Review the note\n\n"
        "```tutorial-step\n"
        "required_patterns:\n"
        "  - cat notes.txt\n"
        "  - tutorial\n"
        "check_command: grep -q tutorial notes.txt\n"
        "```\n\n"
        "Display the file with `cat notes.txt`.\n\n"
        "The transcript should show both the command and the file contents.\n"
    )
    return tutorial_path
@
